\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Matrix Representation of a Linear Map
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Michael Nelson
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset toc
LatexCommand tableofcontents

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage newpage
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this note, let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field, let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-vector space with basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=\{\beta_{1},\dots,\beta_{m}\}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-vector space with basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=\{\gamma_{1},\dots,\gamma_{n}\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On a first encounter in linear algebra, one typically studies 
\emph on
concrete
\emph default
 vector spaces like 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\emph on
concrete
\emph default
 matrices like 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\begin{smallmatrix}a & b\\
c & d
\end{smallmatrix}\right)\colon\mathbb{R}^{2}\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 In a more abstract setting, one studies 
\emph on
abstract
\emph default
 vectors spaces like 
\begin_inset Formula $V,W$
\end_inset

 and 
\emph on
abstract
\emph default
 linear maps between them like 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon V\to W$
\end_inset

.
 However, this abstract setting is not as abstract as it may first seem.
 Indeed, it turns out that we can translate everything in the abstract setting
 to the more concrete setting.
 We will describe this translation in this note.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
From the Abstract Setting to the Concrete Setting
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Column Representation of a Vector
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in V$
\end_inset

.
 Then for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

, there exists unique 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}\in K$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v=\sum_{i=1}^{m}a_{i}\beta_{i}.
\]

\end_inset

Since the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

 are uniquely determined, we are justified in making the following definition:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The 
\series bold
column representation of 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
with respect to the basis
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $[v]_{\beta}$
\end_inset

, is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[v]_{\beta}:=\begin{pmatrix}a_{1}\\
\vdots\\
a_{m}
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propcolumnislinear}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $[\cdot]_{\beta}\colon V\to K^{m}$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[\cdot]_{\beta}(v)=[v]_{\beta}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in V$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $[\cdot]_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We first show that 
\begin_inset Formula $[\cdot]_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is linear.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1},v_{2}\in V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1},c_{2}\in K$
\end_inset

.
 Then for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

, there exists unique 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i1},a_{i2}\in K$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{1}=\sum_{i=1}^{m}a_{i1}\beta_{i}\quad\text{and}\quad v_{2}=\sum_{i=1}^{m}a_{i2}\beta_{i}.
\]

\end_inset

 Therefore we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
a_{1}v_{1}+a_{2}v_{2} & =a_{1}\sum_{i=1}^{m}a_{i1}\beta_{i}+a_{2}\sum_{i=1}^{m}a_{i2}\beta_{i}\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{m}(a_{1}a_{i1}+a_{2}a_{i2})\beta_{i}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
[a_{1}v_{1}+a_{2}v_{2}]_{\beta} & =\begin{pmatrix}a_{1}a_{11}+a_{2}a_{12}\\
\vdots\\
a_{1}a_{m1}+a_{2}a_{m2}
\end{pmatrix}\\
 & =a_{1}\begin{pmatrix}a_{11}\\
\vdots\\
a_{m1}
\end{pmatrix}+a_{2}\begin{pmatrix}a_{12}\\
\vdots\\
a_{m2}
\end{pmatrix}\\
 & =a_{1}[v_{1}]_{\beta}+a_{2}[v_{2}]_{\beta}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $[\cdot]_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is linear.
 To see that 
\begin_inset Formula $[\cdot]_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $[\beta_{i}]=e_{i}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the column vector in 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{n}$
\end_inset

 whose 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th entry is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and whose entry everywhere else is 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $[\cdot]_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 restricts to a bijection on basis sets
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[\cdot]_{\beta}\colon\{\beta_{1},\dots,\beta_{m}\}\to\{e_{1},\dots,e_{n}\},
\]

\end_inset

and so it must be an isomorphism.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Matrix Representation of a Linear Map
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 be a linear map from 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 Then for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq j\leq n$
\end_inset

, there exists unique elements 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ji}\in K$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T(\beta_{i})=\sum_{j=1}^{n}a_{ji}\gamma_{j}\label{eq:matrixrepeq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

.
 Since the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ji}$
\end_inset

 are uniquely determined, we are justified in making the following definition:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The 
\series bold
matrix representation of
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
with respect to the bases
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
and
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $[T]_{\beta}^{\gamma}$
\end_inset

, is defined to be the 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times m$
\end_inset

 matrix
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[T]_{\beta}^{\gamma}:=\begin{pmatrix}a_{11} & \cdots & a_{1m}\\
\vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
a_{n1} & \cdots & a_{nm}
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propcommutative}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 be a linear map from 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[T]_{\beta}^{\gamma}[v]_{\beta}=[T(v)]_{\gamma}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in V$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In terms of diagrams, this proposition says that the following diagram
 is commutative
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} K^m 
\backslash
arrow[r, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\backslash
text{[}T 
\backslash
text{]}^{
\backslash
gamma }_{
\backslash
beta } 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

] & K^n  
\backslash

\backslash
 V 
\backslash
arrow[u, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

 
\backslash
text{[} 
\backslash
cdot  
\backslash
text{]} _{
\backslash
beta } 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

] 
\backslash
arrow[r, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

T
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, swap]  & W  
\backslash
arrow[u, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

 
\backslash
text{[} 
\backslash
cdot 
\backslash
text{]} _{
\backslash
gamma } 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

, swap]    
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in V$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i},a_{ji}\in K$
\end_inset

 be the unique elements such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v=\sum_{i=1}^{m}a_{i}\beta_{i}\quad\text{and}\quad T(\beta_{i})=\sum_{j=1}^{n}a_{ji}\gamma_{j}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
[T]_{\beta}^{\gamma}[v]_{\beta} & =\begin{pmatrix}a_{11} & \cdots & a_{1m}\\
\vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
a_{n1} & \cdots & a_{nm}
\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}a_{1}\\
\vdots\\
a_{m}
\end{pmatrix}\\
 & =\begin{pmatrix}\sum_{i=1}^{m}a_{1i}a_{i}\\
\vdots\\
\sum_{i=1}^{m}a_{ni}a_{i}
\end{pmatrix}\\
 & =[T(v)]_{\gamma}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Where the last equality follows from 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
T(v) & =T\left(\sum_{i=1}^{m}a_{i}\beta_{i}\right)\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{m}a_{i}T(\beta_{i})\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{m}a_{i}\sum_{j=1}^{n}a_{ji}\gamma_{j}\\
 & =\sum_{j=1}^{n}\left(\sum_{i=1}^{m}a_{ji}a_{i}\right)\gamma_{j}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theoremcomptomatrixmult}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $V'$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $V''$
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-vector spaces with bases 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta'$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta''$
\end_inset

 respectively and let 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon V\to V'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T'\colon V'\to V''$
\end_inset

 be two 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-linear maps.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[T'\circ T]_{\beta}^{\beta''}=[T']_{\beta'}^{\beta''}[T]_{\beta}^{\beta'}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $[v]_{\beta}\in K^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
[T'\circ T]_{\beta}^{\beta''}[v]_{\beta} & =[(T'\circ T)(v)]_{\beta''}\\
 & =[T'(T(v))]_{\beta''}\\
 & =[T']_{\beta'}^{\beta''}[T(v)]_{\beta'}\\
 & =[T']_{\beta'}^{\beta''}[T]_{\beta}^{\beta'}[v]_{\beta}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $[T'\circ T]_{\beta}^{\beta''}=[T']_{\beta'}^{\beta''}[T]_{\beta}^{\beta'}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Change of Basis Matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this subsection, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 be another basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 be another basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $1_{V}\colon V\to V$
\end_inset

 denote the identity map.
 The 
\series bold
change of basis matrix from 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is defined to be the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $[1_{V}]_{\alpha}^{\beta}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The reason why we say from 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and not from 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is because we want to express the new basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 in terms of the old basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Observe that the change of basis matrix from 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is invertible, with inverse being 
\begin_inset Formula $[1_{V}]_{\beta}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
[1_{V}]_{\alpha}^{\beta}[1_{V}]_{\beta}^{\alpha} & =[1_{V}\circ1_{V}]_{\beta}^{\beta}\\
 & =[1_{V}]_{\beta}^{\beta}\\
 & =\text{I}_{m},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{I}_{m}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times m$
\end_inset

 identity matrix.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In applications, we often describe a change of basis from 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 as a concrete matrix like
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C=\begin{pmatrix}c_{11} & \cdots & c_{1m}\\
\vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
c_{m1} & \cdots & c_{mm}
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

Let us show how to work with 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 in terms of our notation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 be the change of basis matrix from 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C[v]_{\alpha}=[v]_{\beta}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in V$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in V$
\end_inset

 .
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
C[v]_{\alpha} & =[1_{V}]_{\alpha}^{\beta}[v]_{\alpha}\\
 & =[1_{V}(v)]_{\beta}\\
 & =[v]_{\beta}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propchangeofbasismatrix}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon V\to W$
\end_inset

 be a linear map, let 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 be the change of basis matrix from 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 be the change of basis matrix from 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[T]_{\alpha}^{\delta}=D^{-1}[T]_{\beta}^{\gamma}C.
\]

\end_inset

 In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $U\colon V\to V$
\end_inset

 is an endomorphism, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[U]_{\alpha}^{\alpha}=C^{-1}[U]_{\beta}^{\beta}C.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
[T]_{\alpha}^{\delta} & =[1_{W}\circ T\circ1_{V}]_{\alpha}^{\delta}\\
 & =[1_{W}]_{\gamma}^{\delta}[T]_{\beta}^{\gamma}[1_{V}]_{\alpha}^{\beta}\\
 & =D^{-1}[T]_{\beta}^{\gamma}C.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Matrix Notation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon V\to W$
\end_inset

 be a linear.
 A useful way to keep track of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:matrixrepeq})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is to write it using matrix notation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(T(\beta_{1}),\dots,T(\beta_{m}))=(\gamma_{1},\cdots,\gamma_{n})[T]_{\beta}^{\gamma}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using matrix notation, we obtain another proof of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{propchangeofbasismatrix})
\end_layout

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 As matrix equations, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\beta_{1},\cdots,\beta_{m})C=(\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{m})\quad\text{and}\quad(\gamma_{1},\cdots,\gamma_{n})D=(\delta_{1},\dots,\delta_{n}).
\]

\end_inset

Thus, we haveC
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(T(\beta_{1}),\dots,T(\beta_{m})) & =(\gamma_{1},\cdots,\gamma_{n})[T]_{\beta}^{\gamma}\\
(T(\beta_{1}),\dots,T(\beta_{m}))C\cdot C^{-1} & =(\gamma_{1},\cdots,\gamma_{n})D\cdot D^{-1}[T]_{\beta}^{\gamma}\\
(T(\alpha_{1}),\dots,T(\alpha_{m})) & =(\delta_{1},\dots,\delta_{n})D^{-1}[T]_{\beta}^{\gamma}C,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $(T(\beta_{1}),\dots,T(\beta_{m}))C=(T(\alpha_{1}),\dots,T(\alpha_{m}))$
\end_inset

 follows from linearity of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[T]_{\alpha}^{\delta}=D^{-1}[T]_{\beta}^{\gamma}C.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-vector spaces with basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=\{\beta_{1},\beta_{2},\beta_{3}\}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=\{\gamma_{1},\gamma_{2},\gamma_{3}\}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon V\to W$
\end_inset

 is a linear transformation such that the matrix representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

