\begin_layout Subsection
Linear Isomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Hom}_{K}(V,W)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{M}_{n\times m}(K)$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So far, we have shown how to obtain a column vector 
\begin_inset Formula $[v]_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 from an abstract vector 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

, and we have shown how to obtain a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $[T]_{\beta}^{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 from an abstract linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon V\to W$
\end_inset

.
 We've also shown that the column represenation map 
\begin_inset Formula $[\cdot]_{\beta}\colon V\to K^{m}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\emph on
linear 
\emph default
map.
 This means, for example, that 
\begin_inset Formula $[v_{1}+v_{2}]_{\beta}=[v_{1}]_{\beta}+[v_{2}]_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 for any two vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1},v_{2}\in V$
\end_inset

.
 Can we view the matrix representation map 
\begin_inset Formula $[\cdot]_{\beta}^{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 as a linear map? Indeed we can.
 To see how this works, we first need to describe the domain of 
\begin_inset Formula $[\cdot]_{\beta}^{\gamma}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Hom}_{K}(V,W)$
\end_inset

 to be the set of all 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-linear maps from 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 We give 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Hom}_{K}(V,W)$
\end_inset

 the structure of a 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-vector space as follows: If 
\begin_inset Formula $T,U\in\text{Hom}_{K}(V,W)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in K$
\end_inset

, then we define addition of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $T+U$
\end_inset

, and scalar multiplication of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $aT$
\end_inset

, by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(T+U)(v)=T(v)+U(v)\quad\text{and}\quad(aT)(v)=T(av)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in V$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Check that the addition and scalar multiplication as defined above gives
 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Hom}_{K}(V,W)$
\end_inset

 the structure of a 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-vector space.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq j\leq n$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{ji}\colon V\to W$
\end_inset

 be unique the linear map such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{ji}(\beta_{k})=\begin{cases}
\gamma_{j} & \text{if }k=i\\
0 & \text{if }k\neq i
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq k\leq m$
\end_inset

.
 Check that the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{T_{ji}\mid1\leq i\leq m\text{ and }1\leq j\leq n\}$
\end_inset

 is a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{L}(V,W)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theoremiso}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-vector spaces with basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=\{\beta_{1},\dots,\beta_{m}\}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=\{\gamma_{1},\dots\gamma_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have an isomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-vector spaces
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[\cdot]_{\beta}^{\gamma}\colon\text{Hom}_{K}(V,W)\cong\text{M}_{n\times m}(K)
\]

\end_inset

where the map 
\begin_inset Formula $[\cdot]_{\beta}^{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[\cdot]_{\beta}^{\gamma}(T)=[T]_{\beta}^{\gamma}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $T\in\text{Hom}_{K}(V,W)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We first show that the map 
\begin_inset Formula $[\cdot]_{\beta}^{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 is linear.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T,U\in\text{Hom}_{K}(V,W)$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in K$
\end_inset

.
 Then it follows from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{propcommutative})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{propcolumnislinear})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
[aT+bU]_{\beta}^{\gamma}[v]_{\beta} & =[(aT+bU)(v)]_{\gamma}\\
 & =[aT(v)+bU(v)]_{\gamma}\\
 & =a[T(v)]_{\gamma}+b[U(v)]_{\gamma}\\
 & =a[T]_{\gamma}[v]_{\beta}+b[U]_{\gamma}[v]_{\beta}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $[\cdot]_{\beta}^{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 is a linear map.
 To see that 
\begin_inset Formula $[\cdot]_{\beta}^{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $[T_{ji}]_{\beta}^{\gamma}=E_{ji}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{ji}$
\end_inset

 is the matrix in 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{n}$
\end_inset

 whose 
\begin_inset Formula $(j,i)$
\end_inset

-th entry is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and whose entry everywhere else is 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $[\cdot]_{\beta}^{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 restricts to a bijection on basis sets
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[\cdot]_{\beta}^{\gamma}\colon\{T_{ji}\mid1\leq i\leq m\text{ and }1\leq j\leq n\}\to\{E_{ji}\mid1\leq i\leq m\text{ and }1\leq j\leq n\},
\]

\end_inset

and so it must be an isomorphism.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-Algebra Isomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{End}(V)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{M}_{n}(K)$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We write 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{End}_{K}(V)$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Hom}_{K}(V,V)$
\end_inset

 to denote the set of all 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-linear maps from 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 to itself.
 Simmilarly we write 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{M}_{n}(K)$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{M}_{n\times n}(K)$
\end_inset

 to denote the set of all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrices.
 There is extra structure present in 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{End}_{K}(V)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{M}_{n}(K)$
\end_inset

 that is not necessarily present in 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Hom}_{K}(V,W)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{M}_{n\times m}(K)$
\end_inset

; namely, 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{End}_{K}(V)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{M}_{n}(K)$
\end_inset

 have 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebra structures.
 Composition gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{End}_{K}(V)$
\end_inset

 a 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebra structure and matrix multiplication gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{M}_{n}(K)$
\end_inset

 a 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebra structure.
 It's reasonable to suspect that the matrix representation map 
\begin_inset Formula $[\cdot]_{\beta}^{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebra isomorphism.
 In fact, this is indeed the case: 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremiso})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 tells us that the matrix representation map 
\begin_inset Formula $[\cdot]_{\beta}^{\beta}$
\end_inset

 can be viewed as an isomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{End}_{K}(V)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{M}_{n}(K)$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-vector spaces, and 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremcomptomatrixmult})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 tells us that the matrix representation map preserves the 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebra structures (it takes composition to matrix multiplication).
 Combining these two theorems together tells us that the matrix representation
 map 
\begin_inset Formula $[\cdot]_{\beta}^{\beta}$
\end_inset

 can be viewed as an isomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{End}_{K}(V)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{M}_{n}(K)$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebras.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Duality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The 
\series bold
dual
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is defined to be the 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-vector space
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V^{\star}:=\{\varphi\colon V\to K\mid\varphi\text{ is linear}\}.
\]

\end_inset

where addition and scalar multiplication are defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\varphi+\psi)(v)=\varphi(v)+\psi(v)\quad\text{and}\quad(\lambda\varphi)(v)=\varphi(\lambda v)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi,\psi\in V^{\star}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in V$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
dual 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is defined to be the basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{\star}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta^{\star}:=\{\beta_{1}^{\star},\dots,\beta_{m}^{\star}\}$
\end_inset

, where each 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{i}^{\star}$
\end_inset

 is uniquely determined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta_{i}^{\star}(\beta_{j})=\begin{cases}
1 & \text{if }i=j\\
0 & \text{else}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Check that 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{\star}$
\end_inset

 is indeed a 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-vector space and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta^{\star}$
\end_inset

 is indeed a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{\star}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon V\to W$
\end_inset

 be a linear map.
 The 
\series bold
dual 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is defined to be the map 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{\star}\colon W^{\star}\to V^{\star}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T^{\star}(\varphi)=\varphi\circ T
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\in W^{\star}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{\star}$
\end_inset

 defined above is linear.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi,\psi\in W^{\star}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in K$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
T^{\star}(a\varphi+b\psi)(v) & =(a\varphi+b\psi)(T(v))\\
 & =a\varphi(T(v))+b\psi(T(v))\\
 & =aT^{\star}(\varphi)(v)+bT^{\star}(\psi)(v)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in V$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{\star}(a\varphi+b\psi)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $aT^{\star}(\varphi)+bT^{\star}(\psi)$
\end_inset

 agree on all of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, and so they must be equal.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 An important remark here is that to determine whether two linear maps out
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 are equal, we do 
\emph on
not 
\emph default
need to check that they agree on all of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 as we did in the proof above.
 In fact, we just need to show that they agree on the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Matrix Representation of the Dual of a Linear Map
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon V\to W$
\end_inset

 be a linear map.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[T^{\star}]_{\gamma^{\star}}^{\beta^{\star}}=([T]_{\beta}^{\gamma})^{\top},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $([T]_{\beta}^{\gamma})^{\top}$
\end_inset

 is the transpose of 
\begin_inset Formula $[T]_{\beta}^{\gamma}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T(\beta_{i})=\sum_{j=1}^{n}a_{ji}\gamma_{j}\label{eq:land}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ji}$
\end_inset

 lands in the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

th row and 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th column in 
\begin_inset Formula $[T]_{\beta}^{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 since we are summing over 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:land})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq j\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 We compute
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
T^{\star}(\gamma_{j}^{\star})(\beta_{i}) & =\gamma_{j}^{\star}(T(\beta_{i}))\\
 & =\gamma_{k}^{\star}\left(\sum_{k=1}^{n}a_{ki}\gamma_{k}\right)\\
 & =\sum_{j=1}^{n}a_{ki}\gamma_{j}^{\star}(\gamma_{k})\\
 & =a_{ki}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, this implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T^{\star}(\gamma_{j}^{\star})=\sum_{i=1}^{m}a_{ji}\beta_{i}^{\star}\label{agree}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

since both sides of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{agree})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 agree on 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ji}$
\end_inset

 lands in the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th row and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

th column in 
\begin_inset Formula $[T^{\star}]_{\gamma^{\star}}^{\beta^{\star}}$
\end_inset

 since we are summing over 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{agree})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Therefore the transpose of 
\begin_inset Formula $[T]_{\beta}^{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $[T^{\star}]_{\gamma^{\star}}^{\beta^{\star}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Bilinear Forms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
bilinear form 
\series default
on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is a function 
\begin_inset Formula $B:V\times V\to K$
\end_inset

 which satisfies the following properties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
It is linear in the first variable when the second variable is fixed: for
 fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $w\in V$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $B(av+a'v',w)=aB(v,w)+a'B(v',w)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,a'\in K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v,v'\in V$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
It is linear in the second variable when the first variable is fixed: for
 fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in V$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $B(v,bw+b'w')=bB(v,w)+b'B(v,w')$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $b,b'\in K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w,w'\in V.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Moreover, we say
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is
\series bold
 symmetric 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $B(v,w)=B(w,v)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $v,w\in V$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
skew-symmetric 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $B(v,w)=-B(w,v)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $v,w\in V$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
alternating 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $B(v,v)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in V$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 be a bilinear form on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 Pick 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and express them in the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v=\sum_{i=1}^{m}a_{i}\beta_{i}\quad\text{and}\quad w=\sum_{j=1}^{m}b_{j}\beta_{j}.
\]

\end_inset

Then bilinearity of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 gives us 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
B(v,w) & =B\left(\sum_{i=1}^{m}a_{i}\beta_{i},\sum_{j=1}^{m}b_{j}\beta_{j}\right)\\
 & =\sum_{1\le i,j\leq m}a_{i}b_{j}B(\beta_{i},\beta_{j})\\
 & =\begin{pmatrix}a_{1} & \cdots & a_{m}\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}B(\beta_{1},\beta_{1}) & \cdots & B(\beta_{1},\beta_{m})\\
\vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
B(\beta_{m},\beta_{1}) & \cdots & B(\beta_{m},\beta_{m})
\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}b_{1}\\
\vdots\\
b_{m}
\end{pmatrix}\\
 & =[v]_{\beta}^{\top}[B]_{\beta}[w]_{\beta}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\cdot$
\end_inset

 denoted the dot product and 
\begin_inset Formula $[B]_{\beta}=(B(\beta_{i},\beta_{j}))$
\end_inset

.
 We call 
\begin_inset Formula $[B]_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold
matrix representation of
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
with respect to the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Bilinear forms are not linear maps, but each bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 can be interpreted as a linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $V\to V^{*}$
\end_inset

 in two ways, as 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{B}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{B}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{B}(v)=B(v,\cdot)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{B}(v)=B(\cdot,v)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in V$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 be a bilinear form on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $[B]_{\beta}=(a_{ij})$
\end_inset

 be the matrix representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 with respect to the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M=[R_{B}]_{\beta}^{\beta^{*}}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i,j\leq m$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B(\beta_{j},\beta_{i})=a_{ji}.
\]

\end_inset

Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{B}(\beta_{i})=B(\cdot,\beta_{i})=\sum_{j=1}^{m}a_{ji}\beta_{j}^{*}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[R_{B}]_{\beta}^{\beta^{*}}=\begin{pmatrix}a_{11} & \cdots & a_{1m}\\
\vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
a_{m1} & \cdots & a_{mm}
\end{pmatrix}=[B]_{\beta}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 That the matrix associated to 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is the matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{B}$
\end_inset

 rather than 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{B}$
\end_inset

 is related to our 
\emph on
convention 
\emph default
that we view bilinear forms concretely using 
\begin_inset Formula $[v]_{\beta}^{\top}M[w]_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $(M[v]_{\beta})^{\top}[w]_{\beta}$
\end_inset

.
 If we adopted the latter convention, then the matrix associated to 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 would equal the matrix for 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{B}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 be another basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 be a change of basis matrix from 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 be a bilinear form on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[B]_{\alpha}=C^{\top}[B]_{\beta}C.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
[B]_{\alpha} & =[R_{B}]_{\alpha}^{\alpha^{*}}\\
 & =[1_{V^{*}}\circ R_{B}\circ1_{V}]_{\alpha}^{\alpha^{*}}\\
 & =[1_{V^{*}}]_{\beta^{*}}^{\alpha^{*}}[R_{B}]_{\beta}^{\beta^{*}}[1_{V}]_{\alpha}^{\beta}\\
 & =C^{\top}[B]_{\beta}C.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Two bilinear forms 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{2}$
\end_inset

 on the respective vector spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{2}$
\end_inset

 are called 
\series bold
equivalent 
\series default
if there is a vector space isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $A:V_{1}\to V_{2}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B_{2}(Av,Aw)=B_{1}(v,w)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Although all matrix representations of a linear transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon V\to V$
\end_inset

 have the same determinant, the matrix representations of a bilinear form
 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 have the same determinant only up to a nonzero square factor since 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{det}(C^{\top}MC)=\text{det}(C)^{2}\text{det}(M)$
\end_inset

.
 This provides a sufficient (although far from necessary) condition to show
 two bilinear forms are inequivalent.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 be a squarefree positive integer.
 On 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}^{2}$
\end_inset

, the bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{d}(v,w)=v^{\top}\left(\begin{smallmatrix}1 & 0\\
0 & d
\end{smallmatrix}\right)w$
\end_inset

 has a matrix with determinant 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, so different (squarefree) 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

's give inequivalent bilinear forms on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 As bilinear forms on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, however, these 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{d}$
\end_inset

's are equivalent.
 Indeed, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\begin{smallmatrix}1 & 0\\
0 & d
\end{smallmatrix}\right)=C^{\top}I_{2}C$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $C=\left(\begin{smallmatrix}1 & 0\\
0 & \sqrt{d}
\end{smallmatrix}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Another way of framing that is that, relative to coordinates in the basis
 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(1,0),(0,1/\sqrt{d})\}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{d}$
\end_inset

 looks like the dot product 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_body
\end_document
